PriorityQueue in Java
`PriorityQueue` is a class in `java.util` that implements **Queue**, **Collection**, and **Iterable**.
It is a **heap-based priority queue** where elements are ordered according to their **natural ordering** or by a **Comparator** provided at queue construction time.
Key Characteristics
●	No null elements allowed.
●	Unbounded queue but internally backed by an array that grows as needed.
●	Elements are ordered either by natural order (Comparable) or by a Comparator.
●	Provides logarithmic time complexity for insertion and removal operations.
●	Does not guarantee FIFO order; instead, the priority determines the order.
Categorized Methods
1. Adding Elements
●	`add(E e)` – Inserts element into the queue.
●	`offer(E e)` – Inserts element, returns false if unable.
2. Accessing Elements
●	`peek()` – Retrieves head without removing, returns null if empty.
●	`element()` – Retrieves head without removing, throws exception if empty.
3. Removing Elements
●	`poll()` – Retrieves and removes head, returns null if empty.
●	`remove()` – Retrieves and removes head, throws exception if empty.
●	`remove(Object o)` – Removes a specific element.
●	`clear()` – Removes all elements.
4. Searching & Checking
●	`contains(Object o)` – Checks if element exists.
●	`isEmpty()` – Checks if empty.
●	`size()` – Returns number of elements.
5. Iteration Methods
●	`iterator()` – Returns iterator (not guaranteed to traverse in priority order).
●	`forEach(Consumer action)` – Performs action for each element.
●	`spliterator()` – Returns spliterator.
6. Conversion Methods
●	`toArray()` – Converts to array.
●	`toArray(T[] a)` – Converts to typed array.
Java Code Demonstration

import java.util.*;

public class PriorityQueueDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Natural ordering (min-heap)
        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

        // 1. Adding Elements
        pq.add(10);
        pq.add(5);
        pq.add(20);
        pq.offer(15);

        // 2. Accessing Elements
        System.out.println("Peek: " + pq.peek());
        System.out.println("Element: " + pq.element());

        // 3. Removing Elements
        System.out.println("Poll: " + pq.poll());
        System.out.println("Remove: " + pq.remove());
        pq.remove(20);
        pq.clear();

        // Re-add for demonstration
        pq.addAll(Arrays.asList(30, 10, 50, 40));

        // 4. Searching & Checking
        System.out.println("Contains 10: " + pq.contains(10));
        System.out.println("Is Empty: " + pq.isEmpty());
        System.out.println("Size: " + pq.size());

        // 5. Iteration
        Iterator<Integer> it = pq.iterator();
        while (it.hasNext()) System.out.println("Iterated: " + it.next());

        pq.forEach(System.out::println);
        Spliterator<Integer> spl = pq.spliterator();
        spl.forEachRemaining(System.out::println);

        // 6. Conversion
        Object[] arr = pq.toArray();
        Integer[] intArr = pq.toArray(new Integer[0]);
        System.out.println("Array: " + Arrays.toString(intArr));

        // Custom comparator (max-heap)
        PriorityQueue<Integer> maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.reverseOrder());
        maxHeap.addAll(Arrays.asList(10, 20, 5, 15));
        System.out.println("Max-Heap Poll: " + maxHeap.poll());
    }
}

